<P>
GERMAN TIED TO LIBYA HELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The former chairman of a West German firm alleged to have helped Libya make a 
suspected chemical weapons plant has been arrested, the Mannheim prosecutor's 
office said. A spokesman said Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen of the Imhausen 
chemical company was seized in the town of Bochum on suspicion of offenses 
against export laws. Imhausen-Chemie and several other West German firms are 
under investigation on suspicion of evading export laws to help Libya build a 
factory at Rabta. Libya has said the plant will make only medicines, but the 
United States and other Western governments believe it was designed to make 
poison gas. Hippenstiel-Imhausen resigned in March, saying he hoped this would 
help to clear up the affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
