<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, When the sun finally came out, more than halfway through the running of 
the Long Beach Marathon, participants were looking for relief. They found it 
along 2nd Street in Belmont Shore. Volunteers had set up aid stations and were 
handing out paper cups of water to any runner looking for a handout. And along 
with the water to drink, there was water in the air to rinse off the sweat and 
briefly cool the skin. William Fitzpatrick, 36, of Long Beach takes a wet shot 
to the head from a volunteer with a hose. Fitzpatrick finished the 26.2-mile 
course in 3 hours 11 minutes 20 seconds. Steven Wille, 43, also of Long Beach, 
is silhouetted as he slows to a walk to linger in the misty air at the 
water-spray point. Wille's finishing time was 4:10:44. The winning time in the 
seventh annual marathon Sunday was 2:12:27, a course record set by Rex Wilson, 
28, of New Zealand. After a cloudy and cool start, excellent weather conditions 
most runners would agree, Wilson held himself behind the lead pack for the 
first 10 miles and watched the building heat and other physical problems take 
their toll on the leaders. When he took the lead, Wilson kept it to the finish. 
There were 4,021 entrants, including wheelchair competitors, race officials 
said. AXEL KOESTER 
