<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: FIGHT FOR ABANDONED NEWBORN BOY ENDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A newborn boy abandoned three months ago in an automobile in Covina who was the 
focus of a struggle between two prospective adoptive families has been placed 
with an unidentified couple who have been waiting nine years for a white 
infant. 
</P>
<P>
Catherine Tracy, chief deputy for the Los Angeles County Department of 
Children's Services, said the infant's temporary foster mother obeyed a court 
order and surrendered him earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
She had gone into hiding with the baby last week after learning that 
authorities planned to place the infant with another family. 
</P>
<P>
The temporary foster mother and another distraught couple -- who said they had 
seen him daily and become attached to him despite his health problems as a drug 
baby -- had asked for a court hearing. However, a court commissioner declined 
to listen to their arguments, Tracy said, ruling that they had no legal 
standing to address the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
