<P>
IN-N-OUT BURGER RAISES MINIMUM HOURLY STARTING PAY FROM $4.75 TO $6 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Mary Ann Galante, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In-N-Out Burger -- which has eight Orange County restaurants -- has hiked its 
starting salary from $4.75 to $6 per hour, the company announced this week. 
</P>
<P>
The decision means a salary increase for more than 75% of In-N-Out's 1,500 
employees, according to the fast-food company. 
</P>
<P>
California's minimum wage is $4.75. 
</P>
<P>
Rich Snyder, In-N-Out's president, said the increase is intended to encourage 
workers to stay with the chain and "to attract good, quality people" to the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
The pay raise could be particularly helpful in Orange County, where retailers 
face fierce competition for minimum-wage workers. 
</P>
<P>
In-N-Out Burger's Orange County stores are in Anaheim, Buena Park, Costa Mesa, 
Garden Grove, La Habra, Laguna Niguel, Placentia and Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
The company is headquartered in Baldwin Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
May 12, 1989, Friday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Due to a reporting error in an article on May 10, The Times incorrectly stated 
the minimum wage in California. The state's minimum wage currently is $4.25 an 
hour. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
